The string has length 2, so in CNF we must have a production

  S → A B

where A ⇒* t15 and B ⇒* t14.  The grammar even has

  S → NT39 NT49

and among the terminal rules

  NT39 → 't15'
  NT49 → 't14'

so

  S ⇒ NT39 NT49 ⇒ 't15' 't14'.

Hence the grammar does generate the string.  
Yes

To derive a 2‐symbol string in CNF, S must expand in one step to two nonterminals X Y, each of which must then in one step yield exactly one terminal.  The only S‐rules are

  S → NT22 NT81  
  S → NT39 NT49  
  S → NT81 NT42  

so X is one of NT22, NT39 or NT81 and Y is one of NT81, NT49 or NT42.  Checking their terminal productions:

  • NT22 → 't10'  
  • NT39 → 't5', 't7', or 't15'  
  • NT81 has no direct terminal  
  • NT49 → 't14'  
  • NT42 → 't7', 't1', 't3', or 't10'  

None of these can yield 't16'.  Hence no derivation of `t16 t16` exists.

After examining all three S‑rules:

  1. S→NT22 NT81  
     • To get length 3 one side must be length 1 and the other length 2.  
     • NT81 has no terminal rule, so it always yields ≥2 terminals; NT22’s only terminal is t10, not t3.  

  2. S→NT39 NT49  
     • NT39 only yields a single terminal (none is t3 when needed), NT49 has no binary productions.  

  3. S→NT81 NT42  
     • NT81 cannot yield exactly one terminal; NT42’s terminals are t7, t1, t3 or t10, but not t13, so it can't produce the final t13.

No partition of t3 t5 t13 fits any S‑expansion, so the string is not in the language.

We need a binary‐split of the three terminals among the two children of S.  In CNF, if S→XY generates three terminals, one of X or Y must generate exactly one terminal (via a unary rule) and the other must generate exactly two (via a binary tree).  Checking all three S‐rules:

1. S→NT22 NT81  
   • NT22 has a terminal rule only for ‘t10’, not ‘t15’, so it can’t produce exactly ‘t15’  
   • NT81 has no terminal rule at all, so it can’t produce a single terminal  

   The only other split (NT22→2 terminals, NT81→1) fails because NT81 can’t produce any single terminal.

2. S→NT39 NT49  
   • NT39 only produces single terminals (‘t7’, ‘t15’, or ‘t5’), so it could match ‘t15’, but then NT49 would have to produce two terminals ‘t13 t8’ – NT49 has no binary rule, only the terminal ‘t14’.  
   • Any other split fails similarly.

3. S→NT81 NT42  
   • NT81 has no terminal rule, so it cannot produce exactly ‘t15’ alone.  
   • NT42 has no binary rule, so it cannot produce two terminals ‘t13 t8’, nor does it have ‘t8’ as a terminal rule.

No split of three terminals into 1+2 under any of the S‐rules works. Hence the grammar does not generate t15 t13 t8.
